<paragraph blockId="84.[670,1199,1004,1763]" pageId="84" pageNumber="84">
IDENTIFICATION: Useful descriptions and measurements of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1843" box="[879,1139,1239,1262]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Phyllostomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="84" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="discolor">
<emphasis box="[879,1139,1239,1262]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="84">Phyllostomus discolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be found in 
<bibRefCitation author="Goodwin, G. G. &amp; A. M. Greenhall" box="[818,1193,1268,1291]" journalOrPublisher="Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist." pageId="84" pageNumber="84" pagination="191 - 301" part="122" refId="ref94360" refString="Goodwin, G. G., and A. M. Greenhall 1961. A review of the bats of Trinidad and Tobago: descriptions, rabies infection, and ecology. Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist. 122: 191 - 301." title="A review of the bats of Trinidad and Tobago: descriptions, rabies infection, and ecology" type="journal article" year="1961">Goodwin and Greenhall (1961)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Husson, A. M." bookContentInfo="282 pp." box="[670,845,1297,1320]" journalOrPublisher="Zool. Verh. Rijksmus. Nat. Hist. (Leiden) 52" pageId="84" pageNumber="84" refId="ref95767" refString="Husson, A. M. 1962. The bats of Suriname. Zool. Verh. Rijksmus. Nat. Hist. (Leiden) 52: 282 pp. 1 30 pls." title="The bats of Suriname" type="book" year="1962">Husson (1962</bibRefCitation>
, 1978), 
<bibRefCitation author="Power, D. M. &amp; J. R. Tamsitt" journalOrPublisher="Can. J. Zool." pageId="84" pageNumber="84" pagination="461 - 468" part="51" refId="ref99556" refString="Power, D. M., and J. R. Tamsitt 1973. Variation in Phyllostomus discolor (Chiroptera: Phyllostomatidae). Can. J. Zool. 51: 461 - 468." title="Variation in Phyllostomus discolor (Chiroptera: Phyllostomatidae)" type="journal article" year="1973">Power and Tamsitt (1973)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Taddei, V. A." box="[763,943,1326,1349]" journalOrPublisher="Ciencia e Cultura" pageId="84" pageNumber="84" pagination="621 - 632" part="27" refId="ref100692" refString="Taddei, V. A. 1975 a. Phyllostomidae (Chiroptera) do norteocidental do Estado de Sao Paulo. I. Phyllostominae. Ciencia e Cultura 27: 621 - 632." title="Phyllostomidae (Chiroptera) do norteocidental do Estado de Sao Paulo. I. Phyllostominae" type="journal article" year="1975">Taddei (1975a)</bibRefCitation>
, Swanepoel and 
<bibRefCitation author="Genoways, H. H. &amp; S. L. Williams" journalOrPublisher="Ann. Carnegie Mus." pageId="84" pageNumber="84" pagination="323 - 335" part="48" refId="ref93773" refString="Genoways, H. H., and S. L. Williams 1979. Records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Suriname. Ann. Carnegie Mus. 48: 323 - 335." title="Records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Suriname" type="journal article" year="1979">Genoways (1979)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Brosset, A. &amp; P. Charles-Dominique" journalOrPublisher="Mammalia" pageId="84" pageNumber="84" pagination="509 - 559" part="54" refId="ref91807" refString="Brosset, A., and P. Charles-Dominique 1990. The bats from French Guiana: a taxonomic, faunistic and ecological approach. Mammalia 54: 509 - 559." title="The bats from French Guiana: a taxonomic, faunistic and ecological approach" type="journal article" year="1990">Brosset and CharlesÂ­Dominique (1990)</bibRefCitation>
, and Anderson (1997). Two subspecies are often recognized: 
<emphasis box="[998,1016,1415,1438]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="84">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1036,1051,1415,1438]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="84">d</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1071,1199,1415,1438]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="84">verrucosus</emphasis>
(Mexico to northwestern Peru) and 
<emphasis box="[1091,1109,1444,1467]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="84">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1124,1139,1444,1467]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="84">d</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1843" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Phyllostomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="84" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="discolor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="84">discolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(South America east of the Andes to northwestern Argentina; Margarita Island; Trinidad) (Koopman, 1994). 
<bibRefCitation author="Power, D. M. &amp; J. R. Tamsitt" journalOrPublisher="Can. J. Zool." pageId="84" pageNumber="84" pagination="461 - 468" part="51" refId="ref99556" refString="Power, D. M., and J. R. Tamsitt 1973. Variation in Phyllostomus discolor (Chiroptera: Phyllostomatidae). Can. J. Zool. 51: 461 - 468." title="Variation in Phyllostomus discolor (Chiroptera: Phyllostomatidae)" type="journal article" year="1973">Power and Tamsitt (1973)</bibRefCitation>
, however, questioned the recognition of these taxa based on comparisons of specimens from near the supposed contact zone in Colombia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="84.[670,1199,1004,1763]" lastBlockId="85.[128,657,1417,1763]" lastPageId="85" lastPageNumber="85" pageId="84" pageNumber="84">
Our Paracou specimens conform closely with previous descriptions of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1843" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Phyllostomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="84" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="discolor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="84">Phyllostomus discolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and measurements fall within the range of variation previously reported from the Guiana region. Our comparisons of published measurements from throughout the known geographic range of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1843" box="[466,596,1505,1528]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Phyllostomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="85" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="discolor">
<emphasis box="[466,484,1505,1528]" italics="true" pageId="85" pageNumber="85">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[501,596,1505,1528]" italics="true" pageId="85" pageNumber="85">discolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
suggest that 
<bibRefCitation author="Power, D. M. &amp; J. R. Tamsitt" box="[235,539,1534,1557]" journalOrPublisher="Can. J. Zool." pageId="85" pageNumber="85" pagination="461 - 468" part="51" refId="ref99556" refString="Power, D. M., and J. R. Tamsitt 1973. Variation in Phyllostomus discolor (Chiroptera: Phyllostomatidae). Can. J. Zool. 51: 461 - 468." title="Variation in Phyllostomus discolor (Chiroptera: Phyllostomatidae)" type="journal article" year="1973">Power and Tamsitt (1973)</bibRefCitation>
were correct and that there is no current justification for recognizing subspecies.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="86" lastPageNumber="86" pageId="85" pageNumber="85" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="85.[128,657,1417,1763]" lastBlockId="86.[94,622,214,267]" lastPageId="86" lastPageNumber="86" pageId="85" pageNumber="85">
FIELD OBSERVATIONS: We captured 17 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1843" box="[128,400,1652,1675]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Phyllostomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="85" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="discolor">
<emphasis box="[128,400,1652,1675]" italics="true" pageId="85" pageNumber="85">Phyllostomus discolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at Paracou: 14 in groundÂ­level mistnets and 3 in elevated nets. Four of the groundÂ­level captures were in wellÂ­drained primary forest, eight were in swampy primary forest, and two were in creekside primary forest. One of the elevated mistnet captures was made at 18â21 m over a narrow dirt road and two were made at 10â 13 m above a treefall gap in creekside primary forest. Several individuals netted in the dry season were covered with pollen. Most bats were caught singly, but two adult males and two adult females (possibly members of a foraging flock) were taken within a 10Â­minute interval at one mistnetting site in swampy primary forest on 24 October 1992, and anÂ­ other adult female was caught a few hours later at the same place.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
